sublevels.theory:
**while loop** — entry-controlled: condition checked BEFORE the body runs.
```cpp
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    std::cout << i;
    i++;
}
```
If the condition is initially false, the body never runs.

**do-while loop** — exit-controlled: body runs FIRST, then the condition is checked. Guaranteed to run at least once.
```cpp
int i = 0;
do {
    std::cout << i;
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
```
Note: `do-while` ends with a semicolon after `while(...)`.

**`break` and `continue` in while loops:**
```cpp
while (true) {
    int x; std::cin >> x;
    if (x == -1) break;    // exit on sentinel
    if (x < 0) continue;   // skip negatives
    process(x);
}
```

**Input validation with do-while:**
```cpp
int n;
do {
    std::cout << "Enter a positive number: ";
    std::cin >> n;
} while (n <= 0);
```

**Loop flag pattern:**
```cpp
bool found = false;
while (!found) { ... }
```

**Avoiding infinite loops:** always ensure the loop condition eventually becomes false.
